<p>Chardonnay's flavor spectrum spans from lean and mineral (unoaked styles) to rich and creamy (barrel-fermented versions). Oak aging introduces vanilla, spice, and buttery notes through malolactic fermentation, which converts sharp malic acid to softer lactic acid. The wine's medium to full body provides substantial mouthfeel and aging potential.</p>

<p>Sauvignon Blanc maintains a more consistent flavor profile across regions, though terroir influences intensity. New Zealand expressions emphasize tropical fruit and intense herbaceousness, while French Sancerre showcases mineral precision. The grape's high natural acidity—typically 6-7 g/L compared to Chardonnay's 5-6 g/L—creates its signature crispness and food-friendly character.</p>

